## Troubleshooting

**"python is not recognized as an internal or external command"**
Python is not in your system PATH. Either reinstall Python and check "Add Python to PATH", or use the full path to python (e.g., `C:\Users\you\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python314\python.exe`).

**"No module named pypdf" or "No module named reportlab"**
You need to install the dependencies. Run `pip install pypdf reportlab`. If you have multiple Python versions, try `pip3 install pypdf reportlab`.

**"KeyError: 'Date'" or similar column errors**
Your CSV column headers may have extra whitespace or a BOM character. The script handles most cases automatically, but double-check that your CSV header row matches the expected column names listed in the [CSV Format](#csv-format) section. Opening the CSV in a plain text editor (not Excel) is the easiest way to verify.

**"No participants match the given filters."**
Your filter values don't match anything in the CSV. Remember that date and timeslot values must match exactly what's in the CSV (e.g., `22MAR26`, not `March 22`). The filters are case-insensitive, so `run` and `Run` both work.

**First page looks fine but other pages are blank**
Make sure you are using the latest version of the script. Earlier versions had a bug related to copying PDF pages. The current version re-reads the blank form for every page to avoid this.

**The PDF doesn't open automatically**
The script tries to open the file in your default PDF viewer. If it can't, it will print the file path so you can open it manually. On Windows, make sure you have a PDF viewer installed (Adobe Reader, Edge, etc.).

**Text is misaligned on the form**
The coordinate layout was calibrated against the NAVPERS 6110/11 (Rev. 12-2025) form saved as a specific PDF. If you are using a different version of the form or a differently-exported PDF, the text positions may not line up. Use the same blank form PDF that was provided with this tool.
